Is the isotopic composition different between the species and the areas?

PERMANOVA is a non-parametric test used to compare differences between groups based on a distance matrix. It is used for multivariate data, where the response is composed of multiple variables. It does not assume normality and is based on permutations rather than parametric distributions. Null Hypothesis (H₀): The centroids of the groups in multivariate space are the same (i.e., there is no difference in the community structure or multivariate response between groups).

library(vegan)

CN <- samples[,c(15,17)]
CN[is.na(CN)] = 0 

CNdist<- vegdist(CN, method="euclidean")

#PERMANOVA TEST
set.seed(1000)
CN.div<-adonis2(CNdist ~ Area1 + Species + Species/Area1, data=samples,permutations = 9999,method="euclidean") # Area, especie y año como factor

2 Isotopic niche

The isotopic niche was estimated using Kernel Utilization Density estimators (KUDs) using the rKIN R package v1.0.2 (Albeke, 2023).

Niche width and niche overlap among species were reported using the 2D KUD of niche size at the 95% confidence level, which provides a good representation of when data are irregularly distributed (Eckrich et al., 2020).

2.1 Niche width

2.1.1 Niche width per area

#delete cell with less than 3 samples
filtered <- samples %>%
  distinct() %>%
  st_drop_geometry()  %>%
  group_by(grid, Species) %>% 
  filter(n() >= 3) %>%
  ungroup()

filtered <-  as.data.frame(filtered)

# CREATE EMPTY DATAFRAME
KUD_area = data.frame(area = NA, species = NA, ConfInt = NA, ShapeArea = NA)
KUD_overlap = data.frame(area = NA, OverlapID = NA, IOO_95= NA, PGO_95= NA, SWO_95= NA)

# CALCULATE AREA AND OVERLAP
for (i in unique(filtered$Area1)){
   #print(i)
  # estimate niche overlap between 2 species using kernel UD and 3 confidence intervals
  test.kin <- estKIN(data=subset(filtered, Area1 == i), x="dC_corr", y="dN", group="Species",levels=c(95), scaler=2, smallSamp = T)
  assign(paste("test.kin", i, sep = "_"), test.kin)
  
  # Extract the area of each polygon
  kin.area <- getArea(test.kin)
  KUD_area  <-  KUD_area  %>% add_row(
                    species = as.factor(kin.area$Group),
                    ConfInt = kin.area$ConfInt,
                    ShapeArea = kin.area$ShapeArea,
                    area = i)  
  
  # determine polygon overlap for all polygons
  kin.olp <- calcOverlap(test.kin)
  KUD_overlap  <-  KUD_overlap  %>% add_row(
                    OverlapID = as.factor(kin.olp$OverlapID),
                    IOO_95 = kin.olp$IOO_95, 
                    PGO_95 = kin.olp$PGO_95,
                    SWO_95 = kin.olp$SWO_95,
                    area = i)  

  # plot the kernel estimates
   plot <- plotKIN(test.kin, title=" ", xlab="dC", ylab="dN")

   plot <- plot +
   scale_fill_manual(values = c("IOO_95" = "#b2182b", "PGO_95" = "#ef8a62",  "SWO_95" = "#2166ac"))  + 
   scale_color_manual(values = c("IOO" = "#b2182b", "PGO" = "#ef8a62",  "SWO" = "#2166ac")) +
   scale_shape_manual(values = c(16, 16, 16)) +
   coord_sf(xlim = c(-21, -13), ylim = c(7, 16))

  assign(paste("KUD_plot", i, sep = "_"), plot)

  # Save the plot as pdf
  pdf_filename <- paste("SIA/KUD_", i, ".pdf", sep = "")
  #ggsave(filename = pdf_filename, plot = plot, width = 8, height = 6, units = "in", dpi = 300)
}

2.2 Intraspecific competition (ITP)

The intraspecific competition was estimated using the Intraspecific Trophic Pressure index (ITP; proposed by Andrades et al. (2021))

\[ ITP = \frac{\log(Abundance + 1)}{KUD_{ij}} \] and modified from Pelage et al. (2022), calculated as:

\[ ITP_{ij} = \frac{\log(nCPUE_{ij} + 1)}{KUD_{ij}} \]

where nCPUE_ij is the standardized catch per unit effort (individuals of species j /10000 hooks) for the grid cell 𝑖 that we calculated in the Part 1 script and KUD_ij is the KUD of niche size at the 95% confidence level for the species j for the grid cell 𝑖.

# calculate ITP
ITP_grid <-  kud_grid  %>% 
  mutate(ITP = ifelse(Group == "PGO", log(pgo+1)/KUD, 
                  ifelse(Group == "SWO", log(swo+1)/KUD, log(ioo+1)/KUD))) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Group,-ShapeArea, -ConfInt) %>% 
  unique()

Explore the relationship between ITP and species and areas. Observed differences:

  • among species: ITP is higher for swordfish than blue sharks and mako sharks (lowest).
  • ITP in the Mediterranean is lower than in the Atlantic.

2.3 Distance to competitor centroids (CCD)

The mean distance to centroid (CD) provides information on niche width but also on individual distribution within the δ13C - δ15N space (Layman et al 2007). Here, CCD is defined as the mean of Euclidean distances between centroid of receiver and those of their competitors and will be used as a proxy for interspecific competition (Teichert et al 2024). The CCD thus measures the dietary niche proximity of receiver with their potential competitors in the δ13C - δ15N space. We are going to determine the distance between the niche centroids by using the crossdist() in spatstat.geom() (https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/distance-between-two-sets-of-points-in-r/)

2.3.1 Calculate Niche CENTROID and euclidean distances

# calculate mean N and C for each cell
samples %>%
  group_by(grid, Species) %>%
  summarise(mean_N = mean(dN),
            mean_C = mean(dC_corr))  %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(mean_C,mean_N, colour = Species)) + 
  facet_wrap(~grid)

isotopic centroid for each species in each gridcell 

centroid <- samples %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
      group_by(Species, grid) %>% 
      summarise(meanN = mean(dN), meanC = mean(dC_corr))  %>%
      pivot_wider(names_from = Species, values_from = c(meanN, meanC)) %>%
      mutate(meanN_SWO = replace_na(meanN_SWO, 0), meanN_PGO = replace_na(meanN_PGO, 0), meanN_IOO = replace_na(meanN_IOO, 0)) 


# calculate euclidean distances
library(spatstat.geom) 
dist <- centroid  %>%
  group_by(grid)  %>%
  summarise(
    dist_SP = ifelse(meanN_SWO != 0 & meanN_PGO != 0, crossdist(meanN_PGO, meanC_PGO, meanN_SWO, meanC_SWO), NA),
    dist_SI = ifelse(meanN_SWO != 0 & meanN_IOO != 0, crossdist(meanN_IOO, meanC_IOO, meanN_SWO, meanC_SWO), NA),
    dist_PI = ifelse(meanN_IOO != 0 & meanN_PGO != 0, crossdist(meanN_PGO,meanC_PGO, meanN_IOO, meanC_IOO), NA))

3 Mixing Models

We ran species-specific Bayesian Stable Isotope Mixing Models (BSIMM) based on δ15N and δ13C values to estimate the relative contribution of the potential prey items in the diet of the three species.

BSIMM were computed using the MixSIAR R package v3.1.12 (Stock et al., 2018) and run with a generalist type prior, 3 Markov chain Monte Carlo chains of 300,000 draws and a burn-in of 200,000 draws.

The convergence of models was checked using Gelman-Rubin and Geweke diagnostics (Stock et al., 2018; Stock and Semmens, 2016).

The diet-tissue discrimination factors (DTDF) were estimated following Caut et al. (2009) (Table S1).

Prey groups were selected to represent the main potential prey in the diet of the three species (see Table S2)

The appropriate parameterization of the BSIMM was validated through the simulation of mixing polygons, where all consumer data corrected for DTDFs should fall within the bounds of the mixing space (Phillips et al., 2014; Smith et al., 2013).

its <- 1500  #specify the number of iterations ("its")
min_C <- -22  #specify the dimensions and resolution for the mixing region figure
max_C <- -14    #choose values outside the 95% mixing region
min_N <- 5  
max_N <- 17
res <- 250 #resolution of the mixing region figure; reducing this improves performance

##Now RUN the simulation 
step_C <- (max_C - min_C)/(res - 1)
step_N <- (max_N - min_N)/(res - 1)   
C_g <- seq(min_C,max_C,by=step_C) #values must be in ascending order
N_g <- seq(min_N,max_N,by=step_N) #values must be in ascending order
mgrid <- function(a,b) {  #create a grid of values to test for P-I-P
  list(
    x=outer(b*0,a,FUN="+"),
    y=outer(b,a*0,FUN="+")
  )
}
m <- mgrid(C_g,N_g)

3.1.1 SWO

Mixing Polygons

samples <- samples %>%  st_drop_geometry()

sources <- read.table("SIA/MixSIAR/INPUT/prey_sourcesCAN.csv",header=T,sep=",") %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Source, -n)  #always put 13C(x) before 15N(y)

canarias <- samples %>%
  filter(Area1 == "Canarias" & Species == "SWO") %>% 
  select(dC_corr, dN, FL)

mixture = as.data.frame(canarias[,1:2])

TEF <-  read.table("SIA/MixSIAR/INPUT/df_SWO.csv", header=T,sep=",") %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Source) 

Par_values <- array(0, c(its,(nrow(sources)*4+3)))  #create files to store data
p <- array(0, c(its,(nrow(mixture))))
mix_reg <- array(0, c(res,res))
for (i in 1:its) {    #run loops to generate source isotopic signatures, for iterations = 'its'
  v <- array(0, c(nrow(sources),2))
  f <- array(0, c(nrow(TEF),2))
  for (j in 1:nrow(sources)) {
    v[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,1], sd=sources[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C
    v[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,3], sd=sources[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N
    f[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,1], sd=TEF[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C enrichment
    f[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,3], sd=TEF[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N enrichment
  }
  V <- v+f
  hull <- chull(V)  #create a 2D convex hull from the enriched sources
  hull_a <- append(hull,hull[1])  #closes the polygon
  P <- point.in.polygon(mixture[,1], mixture[,2], V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P_I_P 
  P_n <- as.numeric(P)      
  p[i,] <- P_n
  poly_a <- areapl(V[hull_a,])  #calculate polygon area, for evaluating the quantity of iterations
  m$y_f <- m$y[res:1,]  #flip y grid data to resemble axes (d13C=x, d15N=y) 
  m_r <- point.in.polygon(m$x, m$y_f, V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P-I-P for the mixing region
  m_r_s <- matrix(m_r,nrow=res,byrow=F)  #convert vector into square matrix
  m_r_s[m_r_s > 1] <- 1  #point.in.polygon can return '2' or '3'
  mix_reg <- mix_reg + m_r_s
  vals <- c(v[,1],v[,2],f[,1],f[,2],0,0,0)  #concatenate values for this iteration
  Par_values[i,] <- vals  #store values
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)-2] <- poly_a
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)-1] <- i
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)] <- var(Par_values[1:i,ncol(Par_values)-2])
  if (i %% 10 ==0) cat(paste("iteration", i, "\n")) 
}

p[p > 1] <- 1   #point.in.polygon can return '2' or '3'
Probabilities <- colSums(p)/its
#print(Probabilities>0.05)
P <- ifelse(Probabilities>0.05, 1, 0)
sum(P/nrow(mixture)*100)
sum(P)
mix_reg <- mix_reg/its  #convert to 0-1 scale
mix_reg[mix_reg==0] <- NA #make the zeros white
mix_regt <- t(mix_reg[ncol(mix_reg):1,])  #transpose matrix for use with 'image'

image(C_g, N_g, mix_regt, col=colorRampPalette(c("blue", "light blue", "green", "light green", 
             "yellow", "red"))(100), xlab="d13C", ylab="d15N", useRaster=T)
cont <- c(0.05, seq(0.1, 1, by=0.1))
contour(C_g, N_g, mix_regt, levels=cont, add=TRUE, drawlabels=T, lwd=1.9)

##USER INPUT
sources <- read.table("SIA/MixSIAR/INPUT/prey_sourcesCAN_sharks.csv",header=T,sep=",") %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Source, -n)  #always put 13C(x) before 15N(y)

canarias <- samples %>%
  filter(Area1 == "Canarias" & Species == "IOO") %>% 
  select(dC_corr, dN) 

mixture = as.data.frame(canarias)

TEF <-  read.table("SIA/MixSIAR/INPUT/df_IOO.csv", header=T,sep=",") %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Source) 

Par_values <- array(0, c(its,(nrow(sources)*4+3)))  #create files to store data
p <- array(0, c(its,(nrow(mixture))))
mix_reg <- array(0, c(res,res))
for (i in 1:its) {    #run loops to generate source isotopic signatures, for iterations = 'its'
  v <- array(0, c(nrow(sources),2))
  f <- array(0, c(nrow(TEF),2))
  for (j in 1:nrow(sources)) {
    v[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,1], sd=sources[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C
    v[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,3], sd=sources[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N
    f[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,1], sd=TEF[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C enrichment
    f[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,3], sd=TEF[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N enrichment
  }
  V <- v+f
  hull <- chull(V)  #create a 2D convex hull from the enriched sources
  hull_a <- append(hull,hull[1])  #closes the polygon
  P <- point.in.polygon(mixture[,1], mixture[,2], V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P_I_P 
  P_n <- as.numeric(P)      
  p[i,] <- P_n
  poly_a <- areapl(V[hull_a,])  #calculate polygon area, for evaluating the quantity of iterations
  m$y_f <- m$y[res:1,]  #flip y grid data to resemble axes (d13C=x, d15N=y) 
  m_r <- point.in.polygon(m$x, m$y_f, V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P-I-P for the mixing region
  m_r_s <- matrix(m_r,nrow=res,byrow=F)  #convert vector into square matrix
  m_r_s[m_r_s > 1] <- 1  #point.in.polygon can return '2' or '3'
  mix_reg <- mix_reg + m_r_s
  vals <- c(v[,1],v[,2],f[,1],f[,2],0,0,0)  #concatenate values for this iteration
  Par_values[i,] <- vals  #store values
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)-2] <- poly_a
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)-1] <- i
  Par_values[i,ncol(Par_values)] <- var(Par_values[1:i,ncol(Par_values)-2])
  if (i %% 10 ==0) cat(paste("iteration", i, "\n")) 
}

##FIGURE 2: proportion of iterations that each consumer was inside mixing polygon
p[p > 1] <- 1   #point.in.polygon can return '2' or '3'
Probabilities <- colSums(p)/its
#print(Probabilities>0.05)
P <- ifelse(Probabilities>0.05, 1, 0)
sum(P/nrow(mixture)*100)
sum(P)
mix_reg <- mix_reg/its  #convert to 0-1 scale
mix_reg[mix_reg==0] <- NA #make the zeros white
mix_regt <- t(mix_reg[ncol(mix_reg):1,])  #transpose matrix for use with 'image'

cont <- c(0.05, seq(0.1, 1, by=0.1))
contour(C_g, N_g, mix_regt, levels=cont, add=TRUE, drawlabels=T, lwd=1.9)

    v[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,1], sd=sources[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C
    v[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=sources[j,3], sd=sources[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N
    f[j,1] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,1], sd=TEF[j,2])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d13C enrichment
    f[j,2] <- rnorm(1, mean=TEF[j,3], sd=TEF[j,4])  #generate values from norm. dist. for d15N enrichment
  }
  V <- v+f
  hull <- chull(V)  #create a 2D convex hull from the enriched sources
  hull_a <- append(hull,hull[1])  #closes the polygon
  P <- point.in.polygon(mixture[,1], mixture[,2], V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P_I_P 
  P_n <- as.numeric(P)      
  p[i,] <- P_n
  poly_a <- areapl(V[hull_a,])  #calculate polygon area, for evaluating the quantity of iterations
  m$y_f <- m$y[res:1,]  #flip y grid data to resemble axes (d13C=x, d15N=y) 
  m_r <- point.in.polygon(m$x, m$y_f, V[hull_a,1], V[hull_a,2]) #calculate P-I-P for the mixing region
  m_r_s <- matrix(m_r,nrow=res,byrow=F)  #convert vector into square matrix

  mix_reg <- mix_reg + m_r_s

#results <- read_excel("SIA/MixSIAR/results_MixSIAR.xlsx") 
models  <- dir(pattern=".RData") 

results <-  data.frame(mesop = NA, gadipela= NA, squid1 = NA, squid2= NA, gela= NA, largepel = NA, species= NA, area= NA)  

for (i in 1:length(models)) {
  file <- models[i]
  species <- strsplit(file, "_")[[1]]
  area <- sub("\\.RData", "", species[2])  # "can", removing the ".RData" suffix
  
  file_path <- paste("", file, sep = "") # Adjust the path accordingly
  load(file_path)
  posterior_diet_proportions <- jags.uninf$BUGSoutput$sims.list$p.global
  posterior_df <- data.frame(posterior_diet_proportions)
  if (species[1] == "swo") {
  colnames(posterior_df) <- c("bathy","ceph1","ceph2","gadipela","gela")
  posterior_df = posterior_df  %>% 
    mutate(species = species[1], area = area)
  
  results  <-  results  %>% add_row(mesop = posterior_df$bathy, gadipela= posterior_df$gadipela,
                                    squid1 = posterior_df$ceph1, squid2= posterior_df$ceph2,
                                    gela= posterior_df$gela, largepel = NA, species= posterior_df$species, 
                                    area= posterior_df$area)  
  } else {
  colnames(posterior_df) <- c("bathy","ceph1","ceph2","gadipela","largepel")
  posterior_df = posterior_df  %>% 
    mutate(species = species[1], area = area)
  
  results  <-  results  %>% add_row(mesop = posterior_df$bathy, gadipela= posterior_df$gadipela,
                                    squid1 = posterior_df$ceph1, squid2= posterior_df$ceph2,
                                    gela= NA, largepel = posterior_df$largepel, species= posterior_df$species,
                                    area= posterior_df$area)  
    
    
  }
 }

# Reshape the data for ggplot2
library(reshape2)
posterior_melt <- melt(results, variable.name = "Prey", value.name = "Proportion") %>% 
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(Proportion = Proportion*100)

pal <- c("#CA0020","#EF8A62", "#92C5DE", "#0571B0","#F6EEC3","green") 

ggplot(posterior_melt, aes(x = Prey, y = Proportion, fill = Prey)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.4, aes(color = Prey), lwd = 0.6) + 
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.3, outlier.shape = NA) + 
  facet_grid(species~area) +
  labs(x = "Prey groups", y = "Diet Proportion (%)", title = "Posterior Diet Proportions from MixSIAR") +  
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_manual(values=pal) +  # Fill colors using viridis palette
  scale_color_manual(values=pal) + 
  scale_y_continuous(position = "right") +    # Move y-axis labels to the right
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank(),
         strip.background = element_blank())
